│ stop({"edit_points": [[7329, 7333,                                            │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/LoopVectorize.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.          │
│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe crash is an assertion in                        │
│ LoopVectorizationPlanner::computeBestVF(): (BestFactor.Width ==               │
│ LegacyVF.Width || planContainsAdditionalSimplifications(...)) && \" VPlan     │
│ cost model and legacy cost model disagreed\". This means the VPlan-based cost │
│ model selected a different VF than the legacy cost model, but                 │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications returned false, indicating              │
│ (incorrectly) that there were no additional simplifications in the chosen     │
│ VPlan that could justify the discrepancy.\n\nThe reproducer loop has          │
│ trivially foldable operations: %mul = %x * 0, %rem = urem 0, %x, and          │
│ llvm.smax(0,0) -> 0. These instructions can be removed or ignored by          │
│ VPlan-based modeling, reducing cost for certain VFs. The legacy model still   │
│ sees them (unless specifically ignored). The mismatch in cost leads to        │
│ different VF choices, and because planContainsAdditionalSimplifications       │
│ currently filters out instructions that are skipped for vector cost           │
│ computation, it fails to report that the VPlan indeed simplified the          │
│ loop.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe pass aborts immediately during          │
│ computeBestVF. No other transformations occur yet. This confirms it's purely  │
│ a cost-model disagreement case. The assertion path shows BestFactor chosen by │
│ VPlan cost model differs from LegacyVF chosen by                              │
│ selectVectorizationFactor().\n\n3. Root Cause                                 │
│ Analysis:\nplanContainsAdditionalSimplifications() is supposed to detect when │
│ the VPlan eliminated or simplified instructions compared to the original loop │
│ so that a VF discrepancy is allowable. Its current logic returns false for    │
│ any instruction not mapped to a recipe if skipCostComputation(&I, true) is    │
│ true. However skipCostComputation(&I, true) may be true only for vector costs │
│ (e.g. ValuesToIgnore / VecValuesToIgnore) while the legacy scalar cost model  │
│ counted these instructions. In our case, the simplifiable arithmetic and      │
│ intrinsic likely end up in CM.ValuesToIgnore/VecValuesToIgnore for vector     │
│ cost, causing planContainsAdditionalSimplifications to filter them out and    │
│ incorrectly conclude no simplification occurred. Thus the assertion fires     │
│ even though the VPlan removed work.\n\nWe need                                │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications to treat an instruction as a            │
│ simplification if it is skipped only for vector cost computation but not for  │
│ scalar cost computation. The current code passes 'true' unconditionally,      │
│ conflating vector-only skips with genuine non-simplifications.\n\n4. Proposed │
│ Edit Point(s):\nEdit lines 7329-7333 in LoopVectorize.cpp inside              │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications lambda to broaden the condition.        │
│ Replace the single skipCostComputation(&I, true) check with a comparison of   │
│ skip status for vector vs scalar contexts. Treat instructions skipped only    │
│ for vector (i.e. skipped when IsVector=true but not when IsVector=false) as   │
│ additional simplifications. Concretely: compute two booleans SkippedVec =     │
│ skipCostComputation(&I, true) and SkippedScalar = skipCostComputation(&I,     │
│ false); only suppress reporting if the instruction is skipped in both         │
│ contexts. The return condition becomes (!SeenInstrs.contains(&I) &&           │
│ !(SkippedVec && SkippedScalar)). This allows                                  │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications to return true for instructions         │
│ eliminated only in the vector plan, satisfying the assertion guard.\n\nThis   │
│ preserves the original intent of not treating induction/exit/reduction        │
│ instructions (which are genuinely pre-costed and skipped in both scalar and   │
│ vector contexts) as simplifications, while correctly identifying vector-only  │
│ skips as evidence of VPlan simplification.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nBy              │
│ distinguishing between vector-only and universal skips, we allow              │
│ planContainsAdditionalSimplifications to recognize legitimate VPlan           │
│ simplifications for this reproducer, preventing the assertion from firing.    │
│ The functional behavior of cost modeling remains unchanged; only the          │
│ diagnostic/assertion guard is corrected to reflect actual simplifications.    │
│ This resolves the crash without weakening the assertion's correctness.\n"})   │
